Works well on Samsung xcover2 very fast satellite/location seek/lock now that I have access to both the glonass and gps systems, proximity alert option would be nice... quick word of advice to people "not getting access to maps due to no mobile coverage" or "downloading maps" easiest way around this that i use is to simply do a "walk through" at a couple of zoom levels that you usually use while you are at home in good mobile coverage, as the program will cache the map tiles automatically and usually to the SD card if you get the settings correct.. it will cache a lot of tiles though so delete unwanted ones after trip, don't worry if you delete ones you may need later because it simply downloads and caches them again if needed (once you have mobile coverage) also a tip is to turn your mobile to flight mode when out hiking in non service areas as "searching" for a mobile signal will drain your battery faster.. also i have noticed with my mobile once i get past 800 waypoints the program sometimes crashes and corrupts the waypoint file so i rename the file by adding a 1 etc and make a new file with the old name before i start a new trip/hike before i get to 850 waypoints

NOW EVEN BETTER. MAP DOWNLOADS  ARE IDEAL FOR ME.  PS I BOUGHT A GALAXY TAB TO GET THE BEST OUT OF THIS APP...  I was planning to buy a GPS plus UK OS Explorer maps for ¬£400+ until I came across Maverick - ¬£3.17 for the same functionality!  It's fantastic.  I map out walk and bike routes on my PC, and then I scroll the same routes on my Galaxy while linked to wifi - usually twice so I have both 1:25K and 1:50K maps to play with. It takes about 10 minutes to scroll through a 1-week walk. The map tiles are cached to sd card so I don't need a data link while I'm in the hills.  I can also build a route on the PC (I use either Memory Map or Quo2), convert to a track, save in .gpx format and then download to Galaxy in the maverick\tracks directory using the Kies software. I can then check my gps position against the downloaded track.  My wishlist now would be, the ability to display a downloaded track (say in red) while recording the live track in blue. And a waterproof case for a Galaxy Ace with a built in large battery...

I'm successfully and heavily using this on my Samsung Galaxy Player (SGP). The documentation and support aren't exactly the best, but it's enough to get by. The app is wonderful. Doesn't crash, works every time. Configurable caching (though it takes some user effort - see the blog). I have ~20GB of maps on my card. Low hundreds of waypoints really bog it down when loading the list or searching for them, just FYI. A few specific things for people:  ** If it's not tracking with your motion (e.g. car or whatever), hit the blue curved arrow to return to your position and then maps move, not sit static  ** Look at the blog to find specific instructions on setting it up to offline cache to your SD card  ** Definitely worth the price. I have used this for hundreds of miles of driving and hiking and it always works. I'm very pleased.

Otherwise, cannot fault it - you can load whatever maps you like onto your SD Card, or cache them on wifi before you head out. Supports all the maps I could need too - in particular, OS Explorer.

At first I downloaded the free version of this app, and then decided to buy "Pro" version, because I wanted to use more custom folders with downloaded tiles. I bought it only to discover that even "Custom 1" folder that is still working in Free version doesn't work in Pro. "Not a big deal", I thought -- let's write to author, he'll fix this issue in a few days. So I wrote an email, attached all screenshots from free and pro versions, and the answer was "Have you selected 'Custom 1' map?" -- strange, yes? I replied and asked author do he need some more information from my side to troubleshoot the bug? Two weeks passed -- no more answers. Really disappointed. ///    Another reason to buy Pro version was Wikipedia POI. Another disappointment, because 4squares places are in the same list as Wiki articles -- no way to filter out 3-5 Wiki articles from the list of 500 cafe and shops; no way to switch from article in my native language to English, very narrow panel to read article. ///    So I don't recommend to buy this. Better take a look at OsmAnd app -- it has functionality to download the whole country from OSM in one click -- just awesome!
